thinking:
We need to evaluate if the visualization described is misleading. The description: bar chart comparing number of deaths from all causes in 2019 with deaths from/with COVID-19 in 2020-2021, stratified by age groups. Data: 0-19: 2999 vs 44; 20-39: 4650 vs 219; 40-59: 12960 vs 690; 60-79: 26310 vs 4650; 80+: 36650 vs 40214.

The analysis says "The trend clearly shows that the number of deaths from/with COVID-19 significantly increased across all age groups in 2020-2021 compared to the number of deaths from all causes in 2019." But for most groups, the COVID deaths are far lower than total deaths 2019. Only in 80+ group COVID deaths exceed all-cause 2019 deaths. So the statement that COVID deaths "exceeded the baseline mortality in all age categories" is false. That's a misreading: they incorrectly compare across different years: they compare COVID deaths (2020-2021) to all-cause deaths (2019) but they treat them as directly comparable; but total deaths in 2020-2021 (including COVID) might be higher; but the data shown is only COVID deaths vs all-cause 2019, not total 2020-2021. So the claim that COVID deaths exceeded baseline in all categories is incorrect. That's "Incorrect reading of chart" error.

Also could be "Cherry-picking": they only present COVID deaths vs prior year total deaths, not showing total deaths in 2020-2021, which could give impression that COVID deaths replaced all other deaths, leading to inflated impact. But main error is misinterpretation: they claim increase across all age groups, but the numbers show increase only for 80+, maybe for 60-79 it's less (4650 vs 26310). So the claim "increase across all age groups" is false.

Thus misleading aspects: Incorrect reading of chart; possibly Cherry-picking (selective comparison). Also perhaps "Issues with data validity" because they don't mention that all-cause deaths include COVID deaths (or they compare different time periods). But primary is incorrect reading.

Confidence: fairly high ~85.

Intentional? Hard to know. Could be unintentional misinterpretation. The language seems exaggerated, could be bias. I'd assign moderate probability of intentional ~60%? Maybe 55%? I'd put 60% intentional.

Rhetoric types: Information Access Rhetoric: they choose to include only COVID deaths vs all-cause 2019, omitting total deaths 2020-2021. So exists, supports misleading aspects (yes). Confidence ~80.

Provenance Rhetoric: Not mentioned source, methodology, etc. Likely absent. Confidence 70 that it's not present.

Mapping Rhetoric: Use of bar chart mapping values to length; likely appropriate. Not misleading per se. So exists (they used bars), but does it support misleading? Not really; mapping is standard. Confidence 70 that mapping present but neutral.

Linguistic-Based Rhetoric: Title/caption likely includes language "significant increase", "COVID caused major crisis". This language frames interpretation. So exists, supports misleading. Confidence 80.

Procedural Rhetoric: No interactive aspects described. Likely not present. Confidence 70 not present.
